{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":64763,"duration_api_ms":64725,"num_turns":18,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"f87a2198-cd95-4b91-84b5-f93c0a12fe31","total_cost_usd":0.4246255,"usage":{"input_tokens":9,"cache_creation_input_tokens":33622,"cache_read_input_tokens":280486,"output_tokens":2968,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":33622,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":9,"outputTokens":2968,"cacheReadInputTokens":280486,"cacheCreationInputTokens":33622,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.4246255,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed all 5 amendments against actual source code. Four are valid improvements addressing real defects or maintenance risks. One (fr-21-093a1416) identifies a real inconsistency but its proposed fix of a new FailureClass variant adds complexity disproportionate to the risk — the existing design already explains itself with a clear comment and the retry budget difference (5 vs 3) is intentional for the unconfirmed-teardown scenario.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-21-7297fd7b","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified the duplication at lines 1273-1284 and 1325-1336 — the pattern match blocks are identical. This is a straightforward DRY extraction into a helper fn. If the timeout detection heuristic ever changes (e.g., new error variant or different string matching), only one site needs updating. Low risk, clear maintenance benefit."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-093a1416","decision":"reject","rationale":"The classification as TransportFailure when teardown fails is intentional and documented in the code comment at line 1080-1083. The retry_policy.rs shows TransportFailure gets 5 retries vs Timeout's 3 — this is actually correct behavior: an unconfirmed teardown means the process may still be alive, which is a transport-level infrastructure problem, not a simple timeout. Giving it more retries is reasonable because the underlying issue may be transient OS-level process management. Adding a new FailureClass::UnconfirmedTimeout would require wiring through the retry policy, journal serialization, derive_resume_state, and all test fixtures for minimal semantic benefit. The existing design is defensible."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-0153f5fb","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed at line 1557-1563: spawn_background_reap calls force_kill then wait() with no timeout. On Linux, a process in uninterruptible I/O (D state) will never exit, making the tokio task and Arc<ManagedChild> leak forever. Adding a bounded timeout (e.g., 30s) after force_kill is a straightforward fix — if the process doesn't exit, log a warning and drop the handle so the task completes. This prevents unbounded resource leaks in a real failure scenario."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-eeb662d0","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed the bug: fail_run() at line 5138 now swallows snapshot write failures (best-effort), but resume_run_with_retry_internal at line 1147-1158 gates on snapshot.status being Failed or Paused — if snapshot write failed, it stays Running, and resume is permanently blocked. The code comment at line 5133-5136 claims the journal is authoritative via derive_resume_state, but derive_resume_state is called AFTER the snapshot status check at line 1147 rejects the resume. Either the snapshot write must remain a hard failure, or the resume path must fall back to journal-derived status when the snapshot says Running but the journal says failed."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-451f4174","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed at line 985: Command::new(binary) spawns without process group isolation — no setsid, no pre_exec to create a new process group. The signal functions at lines 354-418 send signals to child.id() (a single PID), not a process group. Any child processes spawned by the backend CLI inherit the default group and survive SIGKILL of the parent PID. These orphaned processes can hold ports, files, or other resources and overlap with the next retry invocation. Spawning into a dedicated process group (via pre_exec setsid or negative-PID kill) is the standard fix for this class of problem."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"3acb35e4-76b3-47a5-8cab-db9dc9e42fc4"}
